The transducer then captures this echo signal
In this method, we don't use a continuous wave. Instead, we send out short, separated pulses-each one acting somewhat like a delta function.

Each pulse travels into the tissue, interacts with the structures, and returns as a backscattered echo. The transducer then captures this echo signal, allowing you to measure reflections from specific depths-what we call the range gate.
